// Doit Agent Context: Non-Tool Use / Fallback JSON Scenario (Multi-Turn Stage 8 - command plans)
//
// Entry point: BashToolAgent.run_single (tool_calling = false). The model emits a raw fallback-JSON
// block; execution output and clarification answers are fed back as USER messages.
//
// Stage 8 carries over everything from Stage 7 (multi-window) and adds MULTI-STEP COMMAND PLANS to
// fallback mode too. There is no `execute_plan` tool here, so the plan rides on the FALLBACK JSON: an
// optional `steps` array (one (command, explanation per step) with optional `overview` and
// `rule_triggered: 13`, emitted INSTEAD of a single `command`. It adds NO new LLM context - the plan is
// produced in the SAME generation call (the DoitNonToolUseAgent's JSON) and then executed
// DETERMINISTICALLY by `_run_plan` (the same runner the tool path uses), with no model in the loop.
//
// So every fallback LLM context is EXACTLY as in Stage 7 - ExplainCommand, HowtoAnswerSubcall,
// CrossSessionResolver, HistoryReferenceResolver, DoitNonToolUseAgent, ClarificationAuthor, BashFilter,
// MemoryManager. The only change is inside DoitNonToolUseAgent: its JSON contract gains the optional
// `steps` array, and a `steps` result routes to ExecutePlan (below) instead of BashFilter.
//
// Rule 13 in `sys.doit_system_prompt` + `sys.fallback_system_instruction` direct the model: when the
// USER asks for SEVERAL distinct actions, emit `steps`; for a single command - including a pipe/`&&`
// chain built to ANSWER A QUESTION - keep using `command` (Rule 7/11). A `sys.fewshot_fallback`
// example demonstrates the `steps` plan.
//
// DETERMINISTIC Python checks run BEFORE the main pipeline and can short-circuit (in order):
//   - activity query (is_activity_query): "what did I/you just do" -> answer from history (no LLM);
//                                         "explain ..." -> ExplainCommand; cross-window phrasing ->
//                                         CrossSessionActivityReport (no LLM). Then DONE.
//   - session list (is_session_list_query): "list the shell numbers" -> report list_sessions. Then DONE.
//   - how-to question (is_howto_question) AND NOT a cross-session reference -> HowtoAnswerSubcall, then DONE.
//   - "execute that" (is_execute_suggestion_request) AND a prior suggested_command exists
//                                                      -> run that command through BashFilter, then DONE.
// Otherwise the pipeline runs:
//   1) CrossSessionResolver      - ONLY on an explicit cross-window reference: picks the other session (unchanged)
//   1') HistoryReferenceResolver - same-session resolver; SKIPPED when a cross-session ref fired     (unchanged)
//   2) DoitNonToolUseAgent       - generates/answers; JSON contract gains an optional `steps` array   (CHANGED)
//   3) ClarificationAuthor       - authors the clarifying question; ALSO picks a window (session menu) (unchanged)
//   4) BashFilter                - judges filesystem modification for a SINGLE command                (unchanged)
//   5) MemoryManager             - stores/updates/deletes durable memories after the turn            (unchanged)
//
// Notation: @T is the current turn; a step i WITHIN turn @T is written @T.i. Convention: index < @T = prior turn.


// 0a. ExplainCommand (explain_command) - unchanged from Stage 7.
ExplainCommand[@T]: {
    S: {
        sys.explain_command_prompt
    }

    U: sys.pid.most_recent_command[@T]
}


// 0a'. CrossSessionActivityReport (_answer_cross_session_activity) - unchanged from Stage 7, no LLM.
//      A cross-window activity query resolves the target session and REPORTS its recent command-bearing
//      turns straight from its doit.jsonl. Deterministic. Then DONE.

// 0b. HowtoAnswerSubcall (answer_howto_question) - unchanged from Stage 7. Guarded by
//     `not is_cross_session_reference`, so a cross-session phrasing reaches the pipeline below.
HowtoAnswerSubcall[@T]: {
    S: {
        sys.answer_howto_prompt
    }

    U: env.user_input[@T]
}


// 1. CrossSessionResolver (resolve_cross_session) - unchanged from Stage 7.
//    Fires ONLY when is_cross_session_reference matched, >=1 other session exists, and it is not an
//    exact pid. Picks the other window and its relevant turns; not-confident -> session menu (step 3).
CrossSessionResolver[@T]: {
    S: {
        sys.cross_session_resolver_prompt
    }

    U: {
        env.user_input[@T]
        sys.other_sessions_summary[@T]          // numbered: each other session's pid, cwd, last-active, recent commands (with ids)
    }
}


// 1'. HistoryReferenceResolver (_analyze_references) - unchanged from Stage 7.
//     SAME-session resolver; SKIPPED when a cross-session reference fired.
HistoryReferenceResolver[@T]: {
    S: {
        sys.history_system_instruction          // states the attribution defaults
    }

    U: {
        env.user_input[@T]
        sys.pid.history_metadata_reversed[@T]
    }
}


// 2. DoitNonToolUseAgent - CHANGED vs Stage 7.
//    The fallback-JSON contract gains an optional `steps` array (Rule 13). The system prompt's Rule 13
//    and a `sys.fewshot_fallback` plan example teach the model to emit `steps` when the USER asked for
//    several distinct actions. Context assembly (memory, activity, cross-session vs same-session replay,
//    clarification rounds) is IDENTICAL to Stage 7. A prior PLAN turn replays as a single serialized
//    command-JSON whose `command` is the step commands joined with "; ".
DoitNonToolUseAgent[@T]: {
    S: {
        sys.doit_system_prompt                  // carries Rule 12 (multi-window, Stage 7) and Rule 13 (multi-step plans, Stage 8)
        sys.fallback_system_instruction         // now ALSO documents the optional `steps` array + rule_triggered:13
        If(sys.has_memories[@T]) {
            sys.memory_block[@T]
        }
        sys.activity_block[@T]
    }

    ForEach(@d: sys.fewshot_fallback) {         // now ALSO includes a `steps` plan demonstration (Rule 13)
        U: sys.fewshot_fallback[@d].instruction
        A: sys.fewshot_fallback[@d].response
    }

    If(resp.pid.cross_session_resolver[@T].matched) {
        // Cross-session: the chosen other session's relevant turns, tagged, folded into user_content.
        ForEach(@x: resp.pid.cross_session_resolver[@T].relevant_ids) {
            U: cross_session_note(sys.other.turn[@x])   // "[from your other terminal session (pid ...) in <cwd>]: ..."
        }
    } Else {
        // Same-session replay (Stage 6/7 behavior), folded into user_content to keep alternation.
        // OUTPUT-AWARENESS SAFETY NET: for a follow-up the replayed ids ALSO include
        // get_latest_output_turn_id() (most recent doit turn with real output).
        ForEach(@t: resp.pid.history_reference_resolver[@T].relevant_ids + sys.pid.latest_output_turn[@T]) {
            If(sys.pid.turn[@t].source == "user") {
                U: user_ran_note(sys.pid.turn[@t].command, sys.pid.turn[@t].output)
            } Else {
                U: sys.pid.turn[@t].prompt
                If(sys.pid.turn[@t].command != "") {     // a prior PLAN replays here too: command = steps joined "; "
                    A: sys.pid.tool_call[@t]            // SERIALIZED fallback-JSON: executable=true, command, rule_triggered=1
                    T: sys.pid.turn[@t].output          // SERIALIZED USER message "Command execution output: <output>"
                } Else {
                    If(sys.pid.turn[@t].suggested_command != "") {
                        A: sys.pid.answer_replay[@t]    // SERIALIZED fallback-JSON: executable=false, suggested_command, rule_triggered=9
                    } Else {
                        A: sys.pid.turn[@t].output
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }

    U: env.user_input[@T]

    ForEach(i: pid.clarification_steps[@T]) {
        If(resp.pid.doit_non_tool_use_agent[@T.i].needs_clarification) {
            A: resp.pid.doit_non_tool_use_agent[@T.i]
            T: env.user_clarification_answer[@T.i]
        }
    }
    // Terminal fallback-JSON (model-elected) is ONE of:
    //   - (executable:true, command, rule_triggered:1)                      -> single command (-> BashFilter, then run/hoist)
    //   - (executable:true, steps:[(command, explanation)], rule:13, overview?)   -> a multi-step plan (-> ExecutePlan)   NEW
    //   - (executable:false, suggested_command, rule:9)                          -> how-to answer (suggest, not run)
    //   - (needs_clarification:true, rule:8)                                     -> ask a clarifying question
    //   - (executable:false, response_text, rule:2/3/4/5)                        -> rejection / conversational reply
    // A cross-session task is re-grounded in the CURRENT cwd (Rule 12).
}


// 2'. Plan execution (_run_plan) - NEW in Stage 8 (fallback). DETERMINISTIC, NO LLM, so it is NOT an
//     ACDL context (no messages array, no model call) - described here in prose only. When the parsed
//     fallback JSON carries a non-empty `steps` array, run_single's fallback branch routes it to the
//     SAME `_run_plan` the tool path uses (so behavior is identical across modes): (1) SHOW the whole
//     plan (overview + numbered command/explanation list); (2) ask ONE "Run this N-step plan? [y/N]" -
//     declined -> nothing runs (this plan-level consent replaces the per-command BashFilter LLM judge:
//     a plan does NOT pass through BashFilter); (3) run the steps IN ORDER, each via execute_bash (regex
//     blacklist applies); (4) STOP at the first failed step, skipping the rest. A standalone `cd` is
//     tracked (validated via os.path.isdir, not subprocessed) and session-state builtins accumulate as a
//     prelude for later steps; on success the net cwd/shell-state are hoisted to the parent shell
//     (_hoist_cd/_hoist_shell). The transcript is fed back as a USER message ("Plan execution output:
//     ...") and stored as the turn's output, with executed_command = the step commands joined with "; ".


// 3. ClarificationAuthor (_author_clarification) - unchanged from Stage 7.
//    Authors a clarifying question for an ambiguous instruction; ALSO reused (with a prebuilt session
//    menu, no LLM authoring) to let the user pick which window when CrossSessionResolver is unsure.
ClarificationAuthor[@T.i]: {
    S: {
        sys.clarify_author_prompt
    }

    U: env.user_input[@T]
}


// 4. BashFilter (_filter_bash) - unchanged from Stage 7. Vets the SINGLE-command path. NOTE: a `steps`
//    plan does NOT pass through BashFilter - it is gated by its own plan-level [y/N] (see ExecutePlan).
BashFilter[@T]: {
    S: {
        sys.doit_filter_prompt
    }

    U: {
        sys.filter_user_instruction
        resp.pid.doit_non_tool_use_agent[@T].command
    }
}


// 5. MemoryManager (extract_memories) - unchanged from Stage 7. For a plan, the executed command is the
//    step commands joined with "; ".
MemoryManager[@T]: {
    S: {
        sys.memory_manager_prompt
    }

    U: {
        env.user_input[@T]
        resp.pid.doit_non_tool_use_agent[@T].command
        sys.memories[@T]
    }
}
